text: "Every child comes into the world full of promise, and none more so than Chappie: he is gifted, special, a prodigy. Like any child, Chappie will come under the influence of his surroundings – some good, some bad – and he will rely on his heart and soul to find his way in the world and become his own man. But there's one thing that makes Chappie different from anyone else: he is a robot. The first robot with the ability to think and feel for himself. His life, his story, will change the way the world looks at robots and humans forever."  Brilliant.

text: So, heres what I got from the trailer about the plot.  Geek A wants to make a sentient robot, and he does this by making a robotic police force. Well, thats pretty damned unethical to begin with as not even the most paranoid dreams of Orwell or wettest dreams of Stalin could ever conceive such a thing. A robotic police force (terminator cops) seems like its ripe for abuse, a dictator could come in and turn these machines on people, thus enslaving them.  Veteran B wants to make giant war machines/mechs, and this is "somehow" slightly better because its controlled by a human. Nothing says freedom like cops using armored mechs armed with beltfed 40 mm grenade launchers, heavy machineguns, and anti-tank rockets. And people bitch about cops using tasers and shooting and harassing people.  How about dont build these devices and everybody learn to love and respect each others decisions in life? I mean really, if the cops are going to use terminators (thats what Chappie is) and giant mechs then as far as I'm concerned I'm going to pickup a half dozen AT-4's and a boatload of grenade launchers. I mean really, if I dont need a so called "assualt rifle" to protect myself, why would they need giant mechs and terminators?  Behind the veil of the plot being what constitutes life, I see this as a dystopian where everybody is oppressed/enslaved by killer terminators and mobile suits. Not a future I would want to leave the next generation with.

text: It seriously makes me uncomfortable that the robot and the AI are considered by the film as inseparable. It's not about a "thinking robot". It's about sentient artificial intelligence. Destroying the robot is futile - the program can very well be backed up into another platform. We are living in the age of the Cloud and the Internet of Things, where there is no such thing as a standalone program into itself. Everything is connected, and it would be exponentially more so in the future.  Plot contrivances aside, any attempt to stop an AI with a drive for self-preservation, such as Chappie, is futile the moment it gained rudimentary control of any hardware at all. What can command a robot today can manifest in all of them tomorrow. Our only solution is to be on good terms with our creations.

text: interesting premise, but they still attach AI to a body, whereas AI can be anywhere. The Art department seems to have taken the designs from the robots in Elysium to modify lightly for this film, which wouldn't surprise if we take into the account that it's the same people in all three films (D9, elysium and Chappie). All in all, it's a realistic approach to how robots would be constructed, it has a certain "Boston Dynamics" feeling to it, and tries to separate itself from the "endoskeleton" paradigm as well as from the "ASIMO"-paradigm. Very interesting

But I know it's almost certain that I'm not the only one who's drawing comparisons to another film series about a newly birthed robotic intelligence trying to prove his personhood to a world unsure about his very existence.  Keeping in mind, a lot has changed since that time in regards to our understanding of what practical A.I. might look like. So what we'll make or break this film for me is if they have a new perspective or something to say that wasn't said before.

text: What I find most frustrating about Neil Blokamp is his black and white morality system he puts in all of his films.  At least in Elysium and as it seems to be in this one.  It's about as complicated as Avatar and not really challenging or thoughtful.  Even in this trailer it starts out by spelling out the plot for you.    "A man corrupted by power,"  (A BAD GUY) ....."A man inspired by change," (A GOOD GUY) it leaves almost nothing to the imagination which is disappointing because I think Blomkamp has a really great vision and aesthetic that's atypical for sci-fi movies today.

text: In the movie I'm sure we will all side with Chappie. He seems so innocent and, from what little we can gather, good natured, but I wonder if artificial intelligence is a good idea. It may be, I'm not saying for sure, but as Wolverine said "there are just too many variables involved".    If machines learn to think then we will be completely at their mercy and while they may be able to contained for a time, eventually they will find a way to do what they want to do (good or bad). Going on a bit of a tangent, this whole idea of transferring human consciousness into the digital world (uploading your brain aka Transhumanism), I believe, can only mirror the consciousness of it's human originator  and will be the same only in appearance for the time the created entity chooses to do so.

text: I'm really looking forward to this film. This trailer makes it look like a generic summer blockbuster in many ways. But from reading the synopsis and looking at specific parts of the trailer, It looks like it'll be much more than that. Like a child Chappie will grow with the world around him, he will struggle to fit in (people attacking him) and will be influenced by others (hanging out with people on the street, wearing gold chains), much like a child struggles to fit in and is influenced by others throughout it's years. Showing that perhaps the line between humans and Artificial Intelligence is actually very thin. If this is the case, this will be an excellent movie by Blomkamp.

text: Who gives anyone the right to kill innocent sentient life? Just because the robot was made 'artificially' or out of metal does not mean that it's an abomination marked for death.   Seriously. Women create life all the time. In the womb. Us humans are basically really complicated machines as well, only our components are based down to the molecular level compared to the macro level of a mechanical robot. Carbon or alloy, this is something that displays the charcteristics of life.  What are the characteristics of life? Cells, levels of organization, uses energy, responds to surroundings, growth, and reproduction. (Anyone who says that all life must be made of carbon is shallow minded) -A robot can be viewed as a giant cell. It carries all functions it needs to survive in one package. Without its servos, it's an immobile mess and cannot survive. -Each of its component are a level of organization. Whether that be locomotion, mental processing, sensory systems, anything. -They require an input of energy to operate. Pretty much anything that moves need this. -They can and will respond to stimuli.  -They don't technically have a meants for physical growth but that does not mean that mental growth can be counted out as well. -And just because they don't have a self cotained means of reproducing does not atuomatically state that they can't simply build another one of their kind.    What pisses me off is how antagonist humans in stories like these are way too shallow minded to look past the metal and wire and into the consciousness that is really what makes people... people! Note how I said 'people' and 'human'. 'People' is a concept. 'Human' is a species.

text: Just watched this movie last night. I was utterly disappointed after being a huge fan of District 9. This movie just did not live up to it's expectations. Too much cursing, unnecessary sexual images, outlandish character costumes (which almost made the movie seem like a joke) and most of all the plot was all over the place. I understand the movie is rated R but man it is just unnecessarily and excessively vulgar, when it has no need to be. I thought it would be okay for my younger brother to watch (who's 14) but boy was I wrong. In conclusion, this movie had so much potential because the initial idea they had was great, the cast was pretty good, and the graphics were also absolutely stunning but the movie just let me down. 3/10 - the 3 being for the graphics

text: This movie sucked big time. Now, I was really intrigued with the idea of having robots as a police force, and having a robot with emotions, even if that idea has been done millions of times. But the film squanders from poor character development, being less consistent to the message of the film, and not a whole lot of chemistry from Chappie and that guy from Slumdog Millionaire, forgive me for not knowing his name. With that said, I did enjoy the visual effects and acting, especially with Hugh Jackman's performance because he looked like he was having fun with his villain role, and it was so over the top that it was actually pretty entertaining. So overall, I don't hate it, I just wish that it was as promising as the trailers. And for those who like it, or even love it, then love it as you will. Everybody has a different taste for entertainment.

text: Neill Blomkamp's great fail. Yo-Landi Visser was BRILLIANT but that's the only positive thing abut this movie. Dev Patel failed miserably, never heard of Ninja but I guess he's not even an actor so I'll let him slip by, Brandon Auret should move Viking TV series, or at least lay off sci-fi, it's not for him obviously, Jose Pablo Cantillo solid but can't save the day, and Hugh Jackman? OMG, worse than Nicholas Cage in his latest. (In case you noticed that I haven't mentioned Sigourney Weaver, that's cause it's the same in the movie - almost unnoticeable). It's not even worth downloading unless you are doing it for your 7yo kid (or younger). It's like someone took parts of Short Circuit, Robocop, and AI and mixed them in the worst possible way (whoever saw all 3 knows what I'm talking about) with a touch of brilliant mind of Isaac Asimov. IMDB rating 7.2? Not even worth Rotten Tomatoes' 30%. If you don't agree with this review, please, watch previously mentioned movies (and read a few books) before raging out, ty. A note: you may manage to get your money back but you can't get back the time.

text: Great movie. It has one gory scene in it. Alot of fire arm violence, but it's stuff that we are used to. It's better shot than Elysium. And it doesn't  go for a documentary  look like District  9.   Chappie  himself  is EXTREMELY  likable.   The other characters  are somewhat  annoying. Hugh Jackman starts off great as a bully. But then, later on the movie he comes off as a Jesus  freak. He literally  calls Chappie  a godless  whatever.   It irked  me alot. And I'm  not even a Christian. Visual effects are great. Hans  Zimmer  sound  Track complements the movie. The end is very wishy-washy. It's a 2 hour long movie . I guess it just needed to end. Compared to Blomkamps  previous  films, this movie is more uplifting.   For Americans, those south African  accents  are going to sound really weird. Hopefully, this will be Blomkamps  final  south African, dystopian - future movie. Because  it's safe to say he has exhausted  his visual bag of tricks. I still think he has a good eye for visual effects. I wouldn't  mind a Halo movie  or a transformers  movie from him.   Also, he is not much of a writer. His movies will benefit  from working  with a writer like Alex Garland.  4 out of 5.

text: Meh. This movie was bad, then good, then bad. Extremely predictable (except for one thing near the end that really sent my eyebrow thru the roof) and with some big hard-to-ignore inconsistencies... but after all it's supposed to be a homage to Short Circuit and other similar old-timey 'cpu comes alive' movies, and i found it passable at that. Chappie as a character is UNBEARABLE in his infancy, but quickly becomes quite likeable.  Can't tell if Wolverine's ridicolously exaggerated portrayal of a militaristic, religious nut is either intentional or the result of laughably incompetent script. I mean, how retarded it is to genuinely believe cops would need anti-air armament and cluster bombs to deal with street crime? How did someone like that end up developing cybernetics?!  Also, is Neil Blonkamp ever going to have an antagonist that doesn't incarnate the worst side of militarism? We get it, war is bad. Please mature a bit in the next movie.  Finally, don't know why Sigourney Weaver even bothered to get out of bed for this. But then again she did stuff like "the cold light of day" recently, so this is a massive improvement. And she evidently likes teh moneys.

author: Ally E.

text: Blomkamp,  movies attempt to examine heady topics such as what does it actually mean to be human, the nature of consciousness, and so forth. Since District 9, he's essentially used the same formula for each of his movies however. Their strong points are an attempt to examine interesting topics that make you think (vs just CGI and explosions, etc), great characters, and unique visuals.  The weak points is a serious need for the suspension of disbelief where physical, technical, and plot line issues are ignored in favor of the "big picture" topics (pretty much the same for each movie however...) he wants to examine that makes what could be a great movie, an OK movie. If you enjoyed District 9 and  Elysium, you'll enjoy Chappie. If you didn't enjoy those movies, Chappie is more of the same from Blomkamp. For me District 9 by far his best movie, and he's been unable to re capture that magic of District 9 ever since. I liked Chappie more than Elysium at least, but it's time Blomkamp found a new formula as he's becoming very predictable. The ending of Chappie seems to take right from Robo Cop. Not sure if that was intentional or a mistake, but I thought it was very Robo Cop (talk about a great movie!) esk at the end.  I'd give this one a B, and it could have and should have been an A, maybe even a classic with some tweaks.

text: After District 9 and Elysium it is an another hit for director Neill Blomkamp. I was personally amazed how he approached this subject, it felt fresh, inovative and really funny for a dystopian sci-fi. CHAPPIE was excellently developed as a character who learns about life, people, human values, relationships and the nature of good and bad. I cared abot him and was interested where it was going. Supporting cast took a backseat here as diverse people who form his character and it worked. I also thought that movie mixed action , drama, humour - it is very funny movie by the way very well and for the 2 hour runtime it just flies by. I also really liked the message it sends. Humans are selfish and will always look for a way to exploit everything they can for their own benefit. Yes, some people might be annoyed by over the top villains and some plot hole here and there, but looking at it overall Chappie delivered big time. It had heart and while sometimes it tried to be too ambitious i did not mind. 3.5/5

text: First off, let me say whoever wrote the description of this movie needs to be fired. Nothing about the bots is oppressive. In fact, everything was fine, until the programmer had to fuck it all up. But it's a movie, and movies need conflict. I get that. But surely they could have actually made the bots oppressive, creating a much more understandable conflict, and cutting out all the stupid gangster crap. If they had done this, the movie would have been so much more justifiable, and have the potential for a better ending. About that later. On to another problem. Too much of this movie was spent trying to make me care about a band of street "gangsters" so that I felt something when they were slaughtered by the world's worst marketed weapon. Seriously, a character made a mech with clusterbombs, anti-air missiles, a minigun, etc., and tried to sell it to a police force in South Africa. They failed miserably (the gangsters). Anyway, watch as the robot, Chappie, who had so much potential to be an interesting character, turn into an overly annoying Hollywood-ified "gangster" to match the ones the movie spends about 70% of it's time on. And in the end, witness the most open and meaningless ending ever. There's nothing to spoil, so I'll just do it. The maker dies, chappie figures out consciousness, transitions them both into robot bodies, the gangsters are killed (thankfully) and chappie and his maker run away. That's it. The whole movie was basically meaningless. That's my rant over. CONDITIONS FOR COMMENTING: READ THIS. THE WHOLE THING. Otherwise, politely move on.

text: Matthew's Movie Madness  "Chappie" (2015) RATING: 8/10  A ghetto robot that can think and feel for himself kicks ass, takes names, and fights Hugh Jackman for 2 hours. How shocked I was to learn that this movie was so much more than that.  "Chappie" is the third and most recent film from "District 9" director Neill Blomkamp, co-written with his wife Terri Thatchel, and co-produced by Simon Kinberg (X-MEN: Days of Future Past). Boy, was I fooled big time by the 31% approval rating on Rotten Tomatoes. Who was truly right, this whole time, was the audience. Bless those who spoke the truth.  With an excellent score by Hans Zimmer, Blomkamp directs this science fiction action-thriller almost flawlessly. And for those who see no real character development, just look at Chappie. Played by Blomkamps longtime friend Sharlto Copley in performance capture and voice, HE is the character we should really recognize. Dramatic, funny, and all-powerful, his performance gives this story meaning. A robot that learns to exist in the real world, and by the end of the film, doesn't even feel like a robot at all. Dav Patel plays Deon, Chappie's creator, with realism, and that's all it takes. Sigourney Weaver makes an even stronger performance, and Hugh Jackman plays a cold-hearted, moral-free villain with charisma and confidence, and what's unique is in the end, he gets his in a way I would never have expected. A great cast for a great movie.  Don't let the critics fool you all on this one. Blomkamp DOES have a promising career ahead of him, as long as he continues to do what he does best: action movies with character, originality, and confidence. An ace movie, and one of the best films of 2015.

text: I really don´t understand all these positive reviews for Chappie. I was expecting a good movie, but what I got instead was a mix of boring and depressing scenes, full with over the top violence and just too much gangster-ing. And I know comments like "what the f*ck is wrong with you??" will start raining on me for this, but this just it how I got the movie. To do it justice, though, I really liked the ending, with transfering humans minds into robots. It was original and interesting. And of course the scenes where Chappe was learning stuff were interesting, and the way the gangsters manipulated him. But I still got a negative impression from the movie. And I use to be VERY tolerant with action movies, even enjoying some real bad ones. But this one... just didn´t work.

text: After seeing this movie and the original Robocop back to back it becomes apparent this is just a pathetic ripoff. MOOSE vs ED-209, mega-corporation that sells the police all of their equipment, greed of company employees pitting two competing designs against each other, a confused sentient protagonist. It's like all of the concepts without any of the hilarious satire or originality. Originally would've given this movie a 6.5/10 but after finding out all the core ideas were stolen, I say 5/10. Just watch Robocop (1987) instead and get a few laughs while you're at it.

text: I don't believe In evolution.  I don't believe in AI.  I don't believe consciousness can be transfered.  I'm a Torah believer psalms 119:142/ John 1:1-7  I'll never change my mind about my truthful beliefs. Never. May I rot in hell if I do.   I will say this. I'm not a dogmatic zealot and not a judiazer.  This was a very entertaining movie. Very   It was fun, engaging, original and smart. They are few and far between, these days.  Jackman was a hoot in "Chapie". He was naughty but determined.   He bored me to tears as Wolverine. The Xmen, DC Comic foolery never had my attention. I could barely sit through one of those movies without drooling on myself and wanting to get up and turn the TV off. 🤤😪😴   It was a predictable character and so redundant - (a prideful renegade that doesn't truly know who he is). As fickle as he is arrogant.. YAAAAWN. 😴 Dime a dozen Hollywood stereotyped character. 👎   Hugh definitely redeemed himself in this movie. 😁😎 I like  the way He acted so South African. 😂 Refreshing.  I'm not surprised that the mainstream critics hated it.  I often disagree with mainstream opinion anyway. ;) If is feuled by secular humanistic futility and is as artificial as AI is.  FAKE. 😑  The movie was entertaining and that's all it should be.  It was artistic, fun and visually stimulating. The characters were real and emotionally convincing. The robot was a clever touch and the written behind the characters was superb.  That's what I paid for. Not to be educated in Spiritual, philosophical subjectivity and consequentially bored out of my skull.  Amein.  Shalom 🕎
